  "opinion": "As a woman with a vocational diploma who's spent years working in hospitality, I've seen how stereotypes can quietly shape people's experiences—especially in fields where they don't feel they belong. Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just about people being afraid of failing; it's the weight of expectations that make someone question their own abilities before they even start. When I talk to clients at the diner, I often hear how 'girls aren't good at math' or 'boys are naturally better at science'—these whispers can linger long after the conversation ends. For someone like me, who grew up with a parent who has a master's degree and another who only went to primary school, it's clear how deeply these ideas can affect confidence. I've noticed that in my own life, even small things—like being called 'the quiet one' in math class—can make me second-guess myself. But here's what I believe: yes, we absolutely should address stereotype threat in STEM. It starts with creating spaces where everyone feels seen and valued, not just the ones who fit the mold. Maybe that means teachers who recognize when a student is struggling because of a stereotype, not just because they're tired or need help. It could also mean parents and teachers working together to challenge those old ideas early on. I'm not saying it's easy, but if we can help kids understand that their worth isn't tied to a single subject or gender, we might see real change. After all, in a world where we're all trying to grow and learn, no one should have to carry a weight they didn't choose.",
